<br>
I think there's a great community here and don't think I'm out of line or unwelcome by most in my input. Everyone's opinions don't have to be the same afterall, or life would be boring.<br>
<br>
As a Mage class also (I often state that I love my Mage and when my Necro hits 60 my 41 Mage will get quite a bit of play time.) and am very excited to see what the pets can do when I get them.<br>
<br>
One of the nice things about not having been a 60 Mage for the last year is that I get the goodies without suffering through all the trials like so many had to. (I remember being a Shaman when alchemy was broken completely... sucked.)<br>
<br>
Oh.. and as I was driving home from work a few minutes ago I had another thought that came to mind about the Mage pets.<br>
<br>
There is almost a pet for every purpose. Water, Fire, Earth and Air... each can do better than others in a given situation. Each is the master of one trade and not the jack of all. The Epic was supposed to be the Master of all Trades and the exception to the rule.<br>
<br>
For the Necromancer (Much as the Beastlord) there's only one pet. He's the jack of all trades and master of none. He is the antithesis of the Mage pets on both ends. He can beat some pets in a straight up fight yes, that's because the pets that he can beat were designed for different purposes. If PVP was a concern then you simply have to know which pet to use when. There should never be a time when you don't have a pet for a given situation. Even against EoT. <br>
<br>
It just means you can't scribe one pet and have him do all tasks. That's the reason Mages HAVE so many choices. (Don't ask me what MS was for lol.. I have MS1 and it stinks except for a fun illusion.)<br>
<br>
What do you think?<br>
<br>
Thanks,<br>
Gojirax - 59 Necromancer<br>
